<DOC><DOCNO> AP880704-0023 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0300EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Airbus     07-04 0198</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Airbus,0204</SECOND><HEAD>Aircraft That Crashed In Gulf Is Consortium's Workhorse</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Iran-Jet Crash, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>TOULOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Iran Air plane that the U.S. Navyshot down in the Persian Gulf was one of 243 A300s built by AirbusIndustries and still in service with airlines worldwide, an Airbusspokesman said.   The wide-bodied A300 was the first aircraft put into service bythe European consortium in 1975 and is still the most widely usedAirbus plane.   The Iran Air jet was an A300 B2 model delivered to the airlinein April 1982, said the manufacturer's director of communications,Robert Alizart.   It had recorded 11,448 hours in flight and 8,757 takeoffs andlandings, he said. The plane was one of six A300s Iran Air wasoperating, all the B2 version.   In different seating configurations, the A300's capacity canrange up to about 300 passengers. The A300 B2 has a range of about2,500 miles.   One of the newest Airbus aircraft, an Air France A320, crashedJune 26 while flying low over at an air show near Mulhouse ineastern France, killing three people.   The Airbus consortium is composed of companies from France, WestGermany, Britain and Spain.</TEXT></DOC>